pify and Zoom and the other companies whose inventions made an awful pandem=
ic a lot better for a lot of people.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99d bet (Not Financial Advice=E2=84=A2=EF=B8=8F) that Zoom, Peloton=
, and Shopify are all worth more in five years than they are today, but eve=
n if they go to zero, I don=E2=80=99t see the value in dunking on companies=
 who=E2=80=99ve at the very least made work, fitness, and entrepreneurship =
more accessible and pushed those categories forward because the market over=
valued them.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re guilty of this on both sides: lionizing companies and their f=
ounders for high valuations, and ripping them to shreds when valuations fal=
l.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the weirdest part of a bear market: the people who are rooti=
ng for something other than other people to succeed and humanity to progres=
s are the ones winning. If the long arc of market history is any indication=
, they won=E2=80=99t be winning for long, or over the long-term, but the en=
vironment that it creates in the interim feels super dark.
(And yes, on the other side, idiots like this [ https://email.mg2.substack.=
com/c/eJxFkU1PwzAMhn9Nc5zysXxwyAFpcAIJISEElyppvC2iTUfiMvbvcbcDUhTZcvy-9pMhI=
BzmevGnuSFbrx4vJ_AFzm0ERKhsaVD7nLww0im9vWPJb5Nw2rHc-n0FmEIePdYF2GmJYx4C5rlc=
OziXmh29jkPk3IjgQIELJBLBRB4SBBHUPt58w5IylAE8_EC9zAXYME8TFFyl2OiPiKfWqftOPtL=
Bc16n29Abyj6hwBB6pShuGHBpFAgttdWWSy4st8Ypt-3UI0nsJO-kQQrM67F-n1-e9y-7j6eHX_=
X2_t6WM8tecim5FkZIbbTdqM3gpNQ6hWCCNHfcdls-HeSmLZH8hq91DlZ9mTHONZcDlb-OYYLxW=
iAu_brMUjJeeighjpBuyPBG_gqxP9AalX4k9QGJt5aWa0fUhb0hIhBaE1OhLSPnNFNX-Tf9Az1K=
l-k ] are not people you want to see winning, either.)
A bear market price reset is a good thing in many ways. It=E2=80=99s a much=
 less profitable environment for scammers. Terra doesn=E2=80=99t build up a=
n $18 billion algorithmic stablecoin by promising 20% APY in a market like =
this. A lot of the me-too companies rushing at the same opportunity for the=
 cash grab opportunity will go away. A higher proportion of talent and reso=
urces will flow to the strongest companies, the ones with the biggest ambit=
ions and most differentiated products.=C2=A0
But a bear market attitude reset can be harmful to the extent it encourages=
 dunking on those who=E2=80=99ve tried earnestly and failed and discourages=
 experimentation.
I saw a tweet the other day =E2=80=93 and the person who tweeted it seems s=
mart and nice, and they represent a commonly-held view, so I=E2=80=99m not =
going to call them out by name =E2=80=93 that said something along the line=
s of:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m bullish on cryptocurrency, bearish on nonsensical use =
cases.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Which sounds like a sensible thing to say, particularly in a market like th=
is, but =E2=80=A6 entirely misses how things work. You need experiments and=
 nonsensical applications to get to the useful ones. You need alchemy to ge=
t to chemistry. You need Ars magna to get to the computer. Apple started ou=
t as a nonsensical homemade computer. Facebook started out as a way to cree=
p on Harvard girls.=C2=A0
Bull markets and bear markets are both natural parts of the cycle. Having s=
pent so much time in the former, we were overdue for the latter. My hope is=
 that people don=E2=80=99t stop trying weird stuff and that investors don=
=E2=80=99t stop funding weird stuff.=C2=A0
While bull markets invite scams and unproductive rehashings of old ideas, t=
hey also create an environment in which risk-taking is celebrated and rewar=
ded. Investors flooding the market with cash is a feature, not a bug.=C2=A0
And I=E2=80=99ll say this for tech bubbles: they=E2=80=99re productive, esp=
ecially compared to banking bubbles.=C2=A0=C2=A0
