px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>Einstein&#=
8217;s explanation of planetary motion does not merely correct Newton&#8217=
;s: <strong>it is radically different</strong>, denying, among many other t=
hings, the very existence of central elements of Newton&#8217;s explanation=
, such as the <strong>gravitational force</strong> and the <strong>uniforml=
y flowing time</strong> with respect to which Newton defined motion.</em></=
p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Newton discovered the force of gravity. Einstein th=
rew that idea out, along with uniformly flowing time. So was Newton&#8217;s=
 work for naught? Useless?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Au contraire. &#8220;Although =
there is no force of gravity,&#8221; Deutsch writes, &#8220;it is true that=
 <em>something real</em> (the curvature of spacetime), caused by the sun, h=
as a strength that varies approximately according to Newton&#8217;s inverse=
-square law, and affects the motion of objects, seen and unseen.&#8221;&nbs=
p;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 1em 0;">Keep what&#8217;s true and valuable, discard the rest, try t=
he next thing. Once again, Newton pointed future generations in the right d=
irection.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Newton showed Einstein where to look and what t=
o improve upon. Without Newton, Einstein may have spent his time making tho=
se same discoveries instead of figuring out <strong>general relativity</str=
ong>, and Heisenberg might have spent his time figuring out general relativ=
ity instead of establishing <strong>quantum mechanics</strong>, and so on. =
<strong>Incomplete or even downright incorrect solutions are a necessary pa=
rt of the process.&nbsp;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Alchemy failed, but science p=
revailed. Gravity failed, but science prevailed.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Newton, =
of course, is not unique in his ability to fail in the right direction. In =
